{
  "text": "[59] We computed the corresponding ratios, using the models described in sections 2 -6, for three sets of parameters, (1) r top = 0, r bot = 1, v = c (see section 3), (2) r top = \u00c00.5, r bot = 1, v = c (see section 5), and (3) r top = \u00c00.5, r bot = 1, v = 0.5c (a physically reasonable case). The results are also presented in Table 2 . In all cases considered, model-predicted electric field ratios are in fair agreement with the experimental data of [CITATION_1] . A smaller ratio at a closer distance indicates a more significant shielding effect for smaller values of d/h. It is worth noting that 4.5-m and 11-m strike objects act as transmission lines only at frequencies higher than about 3 MHz (wavelengths shorter than 100 m); at lower frequencies, they act as lumped circuits, since the wavelengths are much larger than the strike-object height.",
  "correct_citation": {
